<div class=3D"article-inc" id=3D"explanation-txt">
    <h1>DETERMINANTS</h1>
<p><br>We know that not every system of linear equations has a single solut=
ion. Sometimes a system of n equations in n variables has no solution or an=
 infinite set of solutions. In this section, we introduce the determinant o=
f a matrix. We shall see in in a subsequent sectionthat the determinant can=
 be used to determine whether a system of equations has a single solution.<=
/p>
<p>&nbsp;Every square matrix A is associated with a real number called the =
determinant of A, written |A|.<br><br>The determinant of a 2 x 2 matrix A,<=
/p>
<p><br><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-te=
xts/articles-imgs/0/1/72/fc648614fd8cfffb86ec66baec0abeff.jpg" width=3D"135=
" height=3D"53" src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/articles-imgs/0/=
1/72/fc648614fd8cfffb86ec66baec0abeff.jpg"><br><br>is defined as<br><br><im=
g class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/articl=
es-imgs/0/1/72/70714ca56ace3631b3da8613982553f7.jpg" width=3D"268" height=
=3D"56"><br><br><br>NOTE Notice that matrices are enclosed with square brac=
kets, while determinants are denoted with vertical bars. Also, the matrix i=
s an array of numbers, but its determinant is a single number.<br><br><b>EV=
ALUATING A 2 X 2 DETERMINANT<br></b> <br>If</p>
<p><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/=
articles-imgs/0/1/72/543ef6e56f8510ae0085cc487f1cca32.jpg" width=3D"105" he=
ight=3D"60"></p>
<p>then</p>
<p><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/=
articles-imgs/0/1/72/58fd7199aae2c2c3c5a0ad519584165c.jpg" width=3D"283" he=
ight=3D"57"><br><br><br><b>DETERMINANT OF A 3 X 3 MATRIX </b></p>
<p>The determinant of a 3 x 3 matrix A,</p>
<p><br><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-te=
xts/articles-imgs/0/1/72/4ed990225223af907a9682e5cc9c0556.jpg" width=3D"157=
" height=3D"74"><br><br>is defined as</p>
<p><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/=
articles-imgs/0/1/72/4dc5d54f8eb94c8b80bba9bc118d3fb4.jpg" width=3D"464" he=
ight=3D"80"></p>
<p>An easy method for calculating 3 X 3 determinants is found by rearrangin=
g and factoring the terms given above to get</p>
<p><br><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-te=
xts/articles-imgs/0/1/72/a14b8903c0ba5f6263d0ef24216e59b0.jpg" width=3D"450=
" height=3D"82"></p>
<p>Each of the quantities in parentheses represents the determinant of a 2 =
X 2 matrix that is the part of the 3 x 3 matrix remaining when the row and =
column of the multiplier are eliminated, as shown below.</p>
<p><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/=
articles-imgs/0/1/72/1e77eaffddfe58334b2241aea8e0b986.jpg" width=3D"300" he=
ight=3D"218"></p>
<p>These determinants of the 2 X 2 matrices are called minors of an element=
 in the 3 x 3 matrix. The symbol M<sub>ij</sub> represents the determinant =
of the matrix that results when row i and column j are eliminated. The foll=
owing list gives some of the minors from the matrix above.</p>
<p><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/=
articles-imgs/0/1/72/fbafdf529deee6bb5b94e6640d48f280.jpg" width=3D"438" he=
ight=3D"177"><br><br><br>In a 4 x 4 matrix, the minors are determinants of =
3 X 3 matrices, and an <i>n x n</i> matrix has minors that are determinants=
 of <i>(n - 1) X (n - 1)</i> matrices.<br>To find the determinant of a 3 X =
3 or larger matrix, first choose any row or column. Then the minor of each =
element in that row or column must be multiplied by + l or - 1, depending o=
n whether the sum of the row numbers and column numbers is even or odd. The=
 product of a minor and the number + 1 or - l is called a <i>cofactor</i>.<=
br><br><b>COFACTOR</b> Let M<sub>ij</sub> be the minor for element au in an=
 <i>n x n</i> matrix. The cofactor of a<sub>ij</sub>, written A<sub>ij</sub=
>, is:</p>
<p><br><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-te=
xts/articles-imgs/0/1/72/936dc3df0a3e8dbfda3a34aa07ce897c.jpg" width=3D"141=
" height=3D"39"></p>
<p><br>Finally, the determinant of an <i>n x n</i> matrix is found as follo=
ws.<br><br><b>FINDING THE DETERMINANT OF' A MATRIX<br></b>Multiply each ele=
ment in any row or column of the matrix by its cofactor. The sum of these p=
roducts gives the value of the determinant.The process of forming this sum =
of products is called expansion by a given row or column. <br><br><br><b>FI=
NDING THE COFACTOR OF AN ELEMENT<br></b>For the matrix</p>
<p><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/=
articles-imgs/0/1/72/ccef023849f1569c4bf131b7892e55aa.jpg" width=3D"85" hei=
ght=3D"86"></p>
<p>find the cofactor of each of the following elements.<br><br>(a) 6<br>Sin=
ce 6 is in the first row and first column of the matrix, i =3D 1 and j =3D =
1.</p>
<p><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/=
articles-imgs/0/1/72/fc72d2628dc7f63d526f66ec2a8455b7.jpg" width=3D"159" he=
ight=3D"46"></p>
<p>The cofactor is (-1)<sup>1+1</sup> * (-6) =3D 1 * (-6) =3D -6.<br><br>(b=
) 3<br>Here i =3D 2 and j =3D 3.<br><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"htt=
ps://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/articles-imgs/0/1/72/e8656293eb4fdcf339f17=
74f31a09862.jpg" width=3D"160" height=3D"58"><br><br>The cofactor is (-1)<s=
up>2+3</sup> * 10 =3D (-1) * 10 =3D -10.<br><br>(c) 8<br>We have i =3D 2 an=
d j =3D l.</p>
<p><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/=
articles-imgs/0/1/72/4dbd8126f64d2cafe0da63f5ed685717.jpg" width=3D"154" he=
ight=3D"48"></p>
<p><br>The cofactor is (-1)<sup>2+1</sup> * (-8) =3D (-1) * (-8) =3D 8.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><b>EVALUATING A 3 X 3 DETERMINANT<br></b>Evaluate</p>
<p><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/=
articles-imgs/0/1/72/e8f98fe351596605868a7bde9adea3d3.jpg" width=3D"120" he=
ight=3D"76"></p>
<p>expanding by the second column.</p>
<p><br>To find this determinant, first get the minors of each element in th=
e second column.</p>
<p><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/=
articles-imgs/0/1/72/679e2ee4a955e6c7d931da0a8902a7b8.jpg" width=3D"356" he=
ight=3D"146"></p>
<p><br>Now find the cofactor of each of these minors.<br><img class=3D"lazy=
load" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/articles-imgs/0/1/72/=
56dcb86c0129ab39126bf439ef6a0d6a.jpg" width=3D"408" height=3D"83"></p>
<p>The determinant is found by multiplying each cofactor by its correspondi=
ng element in the matrix and finding the sum of these products.<br><br><img=
 class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/article=
s-imgs/0/1/72/d2950040140158123e8d1b343157d892.jpg" width=3D"387" height=3D=
"124"></p>
<p><b>CAUTION: </b>Be very careful to keep track of all negative signs when=
 evaluating determinants. Work carefully, writing down each step as in the =
examples. Skipping steps frequently leads to errors in these computations.<=
br><br>Exactly the same answer would be found using any row or column of th=
e ma trix. One reason that column 2 was used in Example 3 is that it contai=
ns a 0 element, so that it was not really necessary to calculate M<sub>32</=
sub> and A<sub>32</sub> above. One learns quickly that zeros can be very us=
eful in working with determinants.<br>Instead of calculating (-1)<sup>i+j</=
sup> for a given element, the following sign checker boards can be used:</p=
>
<p><br><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-te=
xts/articles-imgs/0/1/72/895271a6ccd9074c8e4a81e54721bf50.jpg" width=3D"773=
" height=3D"135"><br><br><br><br>The signs alternate for each row and colum=
n, beginning with + in the first row, first column position. Thus, these ar=
rays of signs can be reproduced as needed. If we expand a 3 X 3 matrix abou=
t row 3, for example, the first minor would have a + sign associated with i=
t, the second minor a - sign, and the third minor a + sign. These arrays of=
 signs can be extended in this way for determinants of 5 X 5, 6 X 6, and la=
rger matrices.<br><br><b>EVALUATING A 4 X 4 DETERMINANT<br></b>Evaluate<br>=
<img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/art=
icles-imgs/0/1/72/08b221c0a5ff0f75a4892e73ce28c7e5.jpg" width=3D"159" heigh=
t=3D"97"><br><br>Expanding by minors about the fourth row gives</p>
<p><img class=3D"lazyload" data-src=3D"https://quickmath.com/solvers-texts/=
articles-imgs/0/1/72/5ba1f53c901c5f5fd6e32caeb845a49e.jpg" width=3D"556" he=
ight=3D"117"><br><br>Each of the four determinants in Example 4 must be eva=
luated by expansion of three minors, requiring much work to get the final v=
alue. Always look for the row or column with the most zeros to simplify the=
 work. In the next section we introduce several properties that make it eas=
ier to calculate determinants. Fortunately, determinants of large matrices =
can be evaluated quickly and easily with the aid of a computer or with cert=
ain calculators.<br><br>&nbsp;</p></div>




